  "text": "Given a state (sample) s of an HA M, an NSC oracle is a procedure for labeling s; i.e., for deciding whether M |= Reach(U ,s,T ). Reachability checker. For nonlinear HA, NSC uses dReal [CITATION_1] , an SMT solver that supports bounded model checking of such HA. dReal provides sound unsatisfiability proofs, but satisfiability is approximated up to a user-defined precision (δ -satisfiability). Simulator. For deterministic systems, we implemented a simulator based on MATLAB's ode45 variable-step ODE solver. Backwards simulator. This is not an oracle per se, but is central to the balanced sampling method. For backwards simulation, we first need to construct the reverse HA ← − M of M. This construction is based on a novel definition of reverse HA which generalizes the one for rectangular HAs given in [CITATION_2] and ensures that reverse trajectories obtained by simulating ← − M are consistent with M. See [CITATION_3] for further details. To generate a positive sample in the context of balanced sampling, we then just need to invoke the backwards simulator starting from an unsafe state.",
